{"query": "How do the effects of amending soil with fresh plant material compare to retaining crop residues in the field?", "summary": "Both approaches show beneficial effects on soil properties, but with some differences in outcomes. For amending soil with fresh plant material or crop remains (Action 910), studies found increased microbial biomass when crop remains and straw were added, improved soil structure when straw was incorporated, and reduced soil loss from erosion in some cases. Six studies found higher soil organic carbon levels when plant material was added, with one finding higher carbon levels when straw was applied along with NPK fertilizers. Four studies reported higher soil nitrogen levels when compost or straw was applied, with one finding reduced nitrate leaching when straw was incorporated. Yield benefits included higher barley yield when straw was incorporated and higher grain yields when crop remains were incorporated earlier in the season.

For retaining crop residues (Action 907), one study found higher microbial biomass when crop residues were retained. A review found reduced water runoff, increased water storage and reduced soil erosion. Two randomized, replicated trials found higher soil organic carbon and nitrogen when residues were retained, with one trial finding this only when fertilizer was also applied. Two randomized, replicated trials found higher yields when residues were retained, with one trial finding this only when residue retention was combined with fertilizer application and no-tillage.

Both approaches work across multiple soil types, with amending covering clay, clay loam, fine loam, loam/sandy loam, loamy sand, sandy, sandy clay loam, sandy loam, sandy-silt, silt loam, silty, and silty-clay soils, while retaining crop residues was tested on clay, loam, sandy-loam, and silt loam soils.", "action_ids": ["910","907","728"]}

